The poem then went on with a long and circumstantial account of the provocations this monarch has given the Israelites, and proved beyond possibility of contradiction that this seeming piece of cruelty, by them inflicted, was nothing more than a just return of vengeance upon his own head for previously treating others in the same inhuman manner. However, the author of the poem concludes his first book with humanely supposing that the Jews did not force him to walk under guard after he was deprived of his toes, or, in his own words,


